<p>
  Most wedding speeches don't fail because the speaker didn't care — they fail because of a handful
  of avoidable habits that are easy to fall into and just as easy to fix, once you know to look for
  them.
</p>

<h2>1. Opening with an apology</h2>
<p>
  "I'm not good at public speaking, so bear with me" is one of the most common opening lines at any
  wedding, and it rarely does what the speaker hopes. It lowers the room's expectations right
  before you need their attention most. Instead, open with the story itself — a specific detail,
  a moment, a first line that pulls people in rather than one that asks for sympathy in advance.
</p>

<h2>2. Trying to cover the whole relationship</h2>
<p>
  A common instinct is to tell the entire history — how they met, every milestone, every inside
  joke — in one speech. It's understandable, but it usually means every individual moment gets
  less room to land. One well-told story, with real detail, almost always beats five stories told
  quickly.
</p>

<h2>3. Borrowing lines that don't sound like you</h2>
<p>
  Quotes, movie lines, and generic vow templates can feel like a safety net, but they tend to flatten
  a speech rather than elevate it. The moments people remember are usually the specific, personal
  ones — a phrase only your friend group would recognize, a memory only you experienced. Borrowed
  words rarely carry the same weight as your own.
</p>

<h2>4. Not accounting for the room</h2>
<p>
  A speech that would be perfect at a rehearsal dinner among close friends can land differently in
  front of grandparents, coworkers, or people who don't know the whole backstory. It's worth a
  quick pass through your draft specifically asking: is there anything here that only makes sense
  to five people in this room? If so, either add a line of context or consider cutting it.
</p>

<h2>5. Skipping practice because "I know what I want to say"</h2>
<p>
  Knowing your material and being able to deliver it comfortably in front of a room are two
  different skills. Speakers who skip practice often find themselves speaking faster than intended,
  losing their place, or realizing mid-speech that a line doesn't land the way it did on paper.
</p>
<blockquote>
  Some moments deserve thoughtful preparation.
</blockquote>
<p>
  Reading your speech aloud, even just once or twice before the day, catches problems no amount of
  silent editing will reveal — awkward phrasing, sections that run long, or a joke that doesn't
  actually sound funny out loud.
</p>

<h2>The simplest fix for all five</h2>
<p>
  Nearly every mistake on this list comes down to the same root cause: writing for how a speech is
  "supposed" to sound, instead of how you actually sound. Our workbook and writing services both
